Adjust racks to top and middle positions and preheat oven to 450 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Dice @Yukon Gold Potatoes{12%ounce} into ½-inch pieces. Cut @Broccoli Florets{8%ounce} into bite-size pieces if necessary. Pick and finely chop fronds from @Dill{1/4%ounce}.

Toss potatoes on a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of @Cooking Oil{} and a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Roast on top rack until lightly browned and tender, ~{20-25%minutes}.

Meanwhile, pat @Salmon{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels{} and season all over with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

> Swap in chicken instead of salmon if preferred.

Heat a drizzle of @Cooking Oil{} in a large #nonstick pan{} over medium-high heat. Add salmon to pan, skin sides down. Cook until skin is crispy, ~{5-6%minutes}. Flip and cook until opaque and cooked through, ~{2-3%minutes} more.

While salmon cooks, toss broccoli on a second baking sheet with a drizzle of @Cooking Oil{} and a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Roast on middle rack until tender, ~{12-15%minutes}.

Heat pan used for salmon over medium heat. Stir in @Chicken Stock Concentrate{1}, 2 TBSP water, and as much chopped dill and @Dijon Mustard{2%teaspoon} as you like.

> If sauce seems too thick, add more water 1 tsp at a time until it reaches a drizzling consistency.

Remove pan from heat; stir in @Sour Cream{2%tablespoon} and @Butter{1%tablespoon}, scraping up any browned bits from bottom of pan. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Slice chicken crosswise.

Divide salmon, potatoes, and broccoli between plates and drizzle with sauce.

Garnish with any remaining chopped dill if desired and serve.

> Use pan used for salmon for the sauce. Skip slicing if using salmon instead of chicken.